WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
Hi, I'm John Helveston, and thanks for tuning in to my lightning talk on how to make R-powered

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.180
surveys with formr.

00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:17.000
If you're someone who has ever had to make a survey, chances are you've probably used

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.280
something like SurveyMonkey or Google Forms, and these platforms work great for simple

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:23.280
surveys.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.040
But what if you needed to make something that was a little more complex than what these

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:28.320
platforms offer?

00:00:28.639 --> 00:00:33.520
Well, thankfully, some really clever people made formr, which uses R and rmarkdown code

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:35.520
to create rich, complex surveys.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:39.119
Now, just to be clear, I'm not one of those clever people.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:43.639
formr was actually developed by Ruben Arslan and Cyril Tata.

00:00:43.639 --> 00:00:48.880
I'm just a formr superfan, and I made this talk to share it with the rest of the R community

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.599
and to demonstrate some of the cool things that you can do with it.

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:53.919
So what can formr do?

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:58.320
Well, I kind of think of it like SurveyMonkey plus rmarkdown.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:02.840
You can use it to create simple surveys, but you can also use R code to generate a much

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.080
richer set of features.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:09.779
For example, you could create interactive charts that survey respondents could then

00:01:09.779 --> 00:01:13.519
experience while taking the survey.

00:01:13.519 --> 00:01:17.279
Or you could use R code to generate dynamic feedback.

00:01:17.279 --> 00:01:22.480
For example, images like this were generated with ggplot code for each respondent in a

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.440
longitudinal study, showing them their risk preferences for different activities based

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:30.400
on their answers to previous questions.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:32.839
So at this point, you might be wondering how all this works.

00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:35.919
So let's dig into some of the details.

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:39.000
Surveys in formr are built using open source components.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.239
The text and code for each survey are input using Google Sheets.

00:01:43.239 --> 00:01:47.599
And once the survey is live, R code is computed using OpenCPU.

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:52.279
This makes it really easy to make your work as transparent as you'd like.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:54.559
So here's an example Google Sheet.

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:58.839
Each row is an item that will be displayed on the survey, and each column controls what

00:01:58.839 --> 00:02:00.680
will be shown.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:05.800
The label column is where you insert markdown or code chunks that you want to display in

00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:07.680
the survey.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:11.520
The type column is where you set the type of each question to show.

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:16.360
You can choose from a long list of options like multiple choice questions, text entry,

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:20.559
or simply just display some text or images.

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:24.240
Depending on the type of question, you may also have some options for respondents that

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:28.199
you want them to choose from, like in a multiple choice question.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:32.080
And you can also customize the look and feel with some styling options.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:37.000
It's kind of analogous to an R markdown document, where the style and question type columns

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.679
are sort of like the YAML, and the label and choice columns contain the content that you

00:02:41.679 --> 00:02:44.320
want to display.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:48.639
Once you've got your spreadsheet ready, you can then log in to formr.org, input the link

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:53.520
to your Google Sheet, and formr will convert it into a survey.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:57.399
The example I just showed generates a survey with some multiple choice questions about

00:02:57.399 --> 00:03:01.600
apples that look like this in a web browser.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:06.479
Once your survey is live, you can then use the associated formr package to go import

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:11.720
results in a nicely formatted data frame directly into R.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:15.360
Now that we know a little bit about how formr works, I'd like to show a couple examples

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.440
of how I've used it in my own work.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:23.160
And I'll start with an example of showing people randomized images in a research method

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:26.039
known as conjoint analysis.

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:31.160
In conjoint surveys, you ask people to choose from randomized profiles of different products.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:35.000
You can then use that choice data to estimate their preferences for attributes of those

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.000
products.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.839
So, for example, if I wanted to know how people felt about the price or freshness of different

00:03:40.839 --> 00:03:46.199
apples, I could ask them to choose from profiles like this, and then in each choice question,

00:03:46.199 --> 00:03:50.440
I'll randomly vary the values that I'm showing them.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:54.399
Because I'm working in R, I can predefine all those profiles in a data frame.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:59.479
So, in this example, the three profiles shown are generated from the first three rows of

00:03:59.479 --> 00:04:02.119
this data frame.

00:04:02.119 --> 00:04:06.479
I've also used formr to create timed randomized quizzes for my class.

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:11.880
I do this by creating a A and B version of every question on a quiz.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:15.880
Then I use the sample function to randomly select a version for each question.

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:19.640
In this example, you might be asked what's your favorite animal or what's your favorite

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:23.239
color depending on which question is selected.

00:04:23.239 --> 00:04:28.720
With just a five question quiz, I can generate 32 unique combinations of quizzes.

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:32.679
And in this particular example, I've also added a timer so that the quiz will automatically

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:35.440
submit when the time is up.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:39.399
So that's just a few examples of how I've used formr, but I encourage you to check out

00:04:39.399 --> 00:04:43.679
formr.org to see some of the other complex designs that you might want to make, like

00:04:43.679 --> 00:04:49.640
longitudinal or diary studies with automated email and text messaging reminders.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:55.239
Today, over a million people have filled out a survey on formr, and there's a growing user

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:57.839
base with a very active support group.

00:04:57.839 --> 00:05:01.559
So you'll have all the help you need to build whatever survey you want.

00:05:01.559 --> 00:05:05.160
So head on over to formr.org and start making some R-powered surveys.

